        "In the realm of deep work, focus is not a passive resource but an active skill that must be trained through repetitive, deliberate practice. When we engage in deep work, we trigger the myelination of active pathways, wrapping our neurons in a fatty sheath that allows electrical signals to travel faster. Conversely, shallow work, characterized by quick task-switching and administrative noise, leaves us in a state of cognitive residue, where part of our attention remains tethered to the previous task. This residue prevents us from achieving full intellectual immersion.",
